text: Kylo meets Palpatine in the first scene on the Sith planet and becomes Palpatiens student.    Secretly tho Kylo wants to team up with Rae and kill him.    Anyways, Rae and the gang go to this desert planet to find some sith dude and some artifact thing to beat the sith.  The first order knows they are there cause Kylo does some weird force thing with Rae and where they can talk to each other like VR FaceTime. Idk.  Lando Calrissian helps them evade the first order for a bit.    Big speeder bike chase through the desert ensues.  The teams kills all the storm troopers and ends up in a cave.  They find the sith ship they were looking for and dagger that has directions to the sith planet etched into it.  C3PO can decipher it though but won’t cause it’s against his programming.  They get out of the cave after Rae uses the force to heal this big snake worm.    Once they leave the cave the first order is hot on their trail.  Chewy gets captured.  Rae fights Kylo and it’s pretty cool.  Then Rae accidentally kills Chewy by blowing up the ship that Chewy is on.  Lol    Then the movie is like “SIKE!” Chewy is actually alive and captured on Kylos star destroyer.    Rae and the gang sneak onto the capital ship to save chewy but they all get captured except Rae.  Rae talks to Kylo with force FaceTime again and then Kylo comes to the ship to talk to Rae and make her come to the dark side.  He tells her that she is actually Palpatines granddaughter.    Then the team escapes.    They go to Yavin-4 to get another sith artifact from the second deathstar.  Rae goes into the death star alone and finds the artifact that would lead her to the Sith planet.  Kylo is there to though and he destroys is.  Then him and Rae fight.  Flin tries to save her but idk what he thought he was gonna do.    Rae kills Kylo when Kylo feels that his mom died via the force.  Then Rae uses that new found force healing power to save his life.  She leaves.  He sees a vision of his dad Han.  Then Kylo joins the light side of the force and throws his lightsaber into the ocean.  BIG WOW    Rae goes Luke and he gives her Red 5.  She takes that to the Sith planet to find and kill Palpatine.  While she meets him the good guys have this huge air to air battle with the new empire fleet.  They are all the old school style star destroyers but each one has a cannon that can blow up a planet.  Pretty cool.  The good guys are WAY out numbered.  Poe is leading them and right before they lose the battle Lando shows up with a metric ASS ton of space ships.    Meanwhile back with Rae and Palpatine, they fight and Kylo shows up.  The Emperor wins and uses that force healing power to steal the life from Rae and Kylo and he is back to full power like in the old movies.  Then he throws Kylo off a cliff.  The Emperor shots lighting into the sky and zaps all the good guys that are fighting the empire ships.  They start to fall from the sky and almost crash.  Almost.  All the jedi ever then talk to Rae via the force and she gets back up and kills the emperor.  She dies again.  Kylo climbs back up and force heals Rae.  She lives.  They kiss.  Kylo dies for real this time.  Good guys win.    Rae goes to Lukes house on Tatooine.  Someone asks who she is.  “Rae Skywaker”  Then she stands looking at the sunset.    Roll Cradits.  Yes this is what happens.  I seent the movie.

text: While I was watching the trailer I noticed some crazy things that contribute to the whole Inception sequel theory.  But first, the theory: Tenet is a palindrome, ten forwards and ten backwards. Inception was released July 13, 2010. Almost exactly ten years later, Tenet will be released on July 17, 2020.  So the setting of Inception takes place in 2010. With that mind I watched the trailer, and noticed 3 vehicles in a chase scene. The 2010 Audi SQ7, 2010 Saab 9-3, and 2011 BMW 5 series. This movie is potentially set in 2010, and Inception takes place during that timeframe

text: "Tenet" will mark ten years since Nolan's "Inception" which many say is the first of a trilogy - "Interstellar" being the middle one - although in that universe's timeline, the order maybe different. Each of those movies deals with the 'time' concept very differently. "Inception" can dilate or slow-down time in dream states, "Interstellar" wraps time through space travel, and so I suspect, "Tenet" may deal with reversed-time or 'anti-time.' Why do I think so? Because the word tenet (meaning strong belief) is also a palindrome - a word spelled the same forwards or backwards.

text: The meaning can be found in the title...as you can see the title's graphic is in reverse/flipped for the last two letters so it basically  does not have a beginning or end. What it does have is a meeting point which is the letter N. let me expand on this.... so lets say the T stands for  "Time" and the E for "ends" and the N for "Now" so if we write in full would be Time Ends Now sdnE  emiT. So its flipped as the timeline in the film as suggested by the scenes in the trailer where time goes backwards even thought we still going forward at the same time. This is obviously a count down narrative confirmed by the tag line that goes "Time runs out" . The climax of the film will be that past and future will meet at the same point in time

text: Am I the only one who took just a hit to notice that time was moving backward every few clips? I love movies, watched thousands and I am genuinely intrigued by this. So is the global threat pockets of randomized time warps? Is time just randomly happening? With all the other time bending movies it is usually a cut&dry situation, something goes wrong (usually in the past) and it must be fixed or changed. This is random areas of time dysfunction? To the point that Robert-P and the main character are talking but some random guard gets flung back a few seconds within a doorway towards the main character. Are our two leads immune to the time dilation? Do they fully know what is going on? I was all ready for a 007 sort of situation with an African American main character then time starts going wonky. I love the ideas and questions this brings up :)

text: Like the internet connecting people across multiple locations in space , tenet is a framework that is planned to connect a single person across multiple instants of his own time.  He gets to connect with his own self from any of the time instants that he has experienced for a duration of ten minutes/seconds/hours and hence the name of the network : TEN NET (Tenet)  Things get weird when somehow a person manages to enter another person’s time lines by breaking into their tenet , thereby causing new events in the other person’s time line and maybe a few suddenly missing events from his own due to this interference between tenets leading to severe time paradoxes.  There’s a possibility of the butterfly effect here where a small tenet interference event would’ve caused an unimaginable consequence, which needs to be reversed.

text: TENET is - Eternalism! It felt like a game with time might seem, but they are very misleading, we are not talking about the cyclical nature of the story. Eternalism and the time loop are two different things that are not interconnected. The first, which was based on a blockbuster based on the multilayered time. All the time coexists simultaneously, but the measurement is determined by the observer. A new way of hybrid warfare! And Christopher Nolan decides to use etherealism as an important link in the plot, then all this is richly visualized with rich action as possible. In my opinion, a magnificent idea for a major spy science fiction blockbuster. Luxurious only because eternalism as a plot combination has never been raised in a big movie. And Christopher Nolan decides to use etherealism as an important link in the plot, then all this is richly visualized with rich action as possible. When I heard those words, I knew where Christopher Nolan was going with this and the way he's presenting just the tease of it in this trailer to the audience in such a realistic yet a manner that seems very plausible is very interesting. This trailer just told us what is film is all about especially at the end showing the release date.

text: Seems like it's about the discovery of something that allows people to manipulate time, but not on a universal basis, but on a item-by-item, person-by-person basis. For instance, the car that flips and crashes "uncrashes" itself. At first, it seemed like Nolan was just rewinding the film, as we've seen countless times. Then it hit me that only the car was rewinding while the car from which we're viewing is moving forward. That's totally eerie.

text: Couple of questions and observations that I've thought of after watching the trailer a bunch of times. 1. The movie is obviously about time travel but how will time travel be done? From the scene with the ships in the ocean and also the car chase scene at the end of the trailer it looks like whatever device or method they use reverses time but leaves individuals unaffected. 2. How far back in time can they go and is there a limit or some kind of physical or existential risk if they keep doing it? Knowing Nolan I'm sure there is. 3. The trailer mentioned that they were trying to stop something worse than nuclear war from occurring. I wonder what that threat could be? I'm thinking that Nolan created a true villian to fight this time, (maybe the guy holding hands with the lady for that short second on the boat? The music seemed to changed ominously for a second when he showed his face on top of that boat or whatever it was and the sun came in behind him) or some evil organization to stop. That could definitely raise the stakes in the movie. John David Washington and Pattison are definitely some kind of time cops so it will be interesting to see how this part of the story plays out. 3. Who is Nolan consulting about the theoretical and scientific basis for time travel? Movies about time travel can open a can of worms especially when they are trying to take a serious approach about it which I'm certain Nolan is doing. Unlike Interstellar and Kip Thorne there is no real empirical evidence or mathematics that we can rely on for time travel. There is a lot of research out there about relativity and Albert Einstein proved much of it years ago. Time travel is a little more complicated in that it is all theoretical. What model of time travel will Nolan rely on? Will he take the butterfly effect model that seems to be the most popular perspective with movies where one event in the past can influence a multitude of future outcomes or will he take the perspective like Steins gate where time is a river and can only be changed by certain actions or events in the past that are dramatic enough to create another timeline? Or maybe he will do a completely different model or a combination of multiple ones. It really has me thinking and I love the fact that Christopher Nolan not only makes movies that are engaging but thought provoking as well. This is going to be fun.

text: More forced diversity

The way the trailer presents this information, it seems like they’re driving backwards in a chase, then the car flips, and then they drive away. But that’s not what’s happening. At the end of the trailer they’re arriving at the scene of a car crash they haven’t caused yet. Pattinson isn’t driving backwards to chase the crashed car. He’s driving forwards, in order to escape the car that he just caused to crash. It’s not the car that is reversing through time, but actually just Pattinson and JDW.”  Essentially, this theory suggests Tenet will see objects (including people) move through time in varying directions and speeds. Even if we don’t know who is pulling the strings, those strings are getting pulled by something.

text: *My Theory:* The main character was part of an organization tasked with fighting insurgents and he passes a high stress training simulation that allows him to join a secret government agency. As he immediately responded "nuclear holocaust" to the woman, I imagine his previous line of work was something related to subduing terrorism.   The secret government agency is combating an issue brought about by foreign weapons testing that ruptures the fabric of spacetime and creates rifts in space where time flows backwards.   Kenneth Branagh is also part of the story and maybe the woman he is seeing is his wife who, having accidentally been in a time rift, had de-aged several years to that of a younger woman. Kenneth's character chooses to be next to her along these rifts but not in them to avoid de-aging with her. Maybe she doesn't want to leave the time rift to be with him because she likes seeing herself become younger, growing more addicted to it.  Also 1:23 suggests that time flows backwards in some of these rifts even if gravity exists normally.   The main characters have to navigate these rifts carefully as to not see their lives move in reverse while looking for the solution to the entire problem. Robert Pattinson helps the main character on this mission.  But it doesn't feel completely proximal since the main character crossed a physical space where time was working in reverse (when they crossed that tumbling car). I'm guessing there is something where people or objects are exclusively immune to the time effects.  Or maybe all this is taking place in someone's mind where time reversal is a way of recalling a memory where one takes steps backwards. Maybe the characters are either in that person's mind or projections of themselves navigating a memory labyrinth.   Idunno. With Christopher Nolan, it's probably something 1000x more mind bending.

text: TENET is a palindrome.    As far as the trailer is concerned it's about a group of people or maybe operatives who are allowed to time travel to the crucial points in the future or past.    The only catch is, they will arrive in the near future of the desired event and the time will rollback till the time fed in the travel machine (or that mechanism) is reached.    E.g. If they decided to be at Bangalore Whitefield Road at 15:00 on the 21st of December 2019 to avoid the misfortunate event,    Then they will arrive at 15:02 or may be 15:03 and will start traveling backward in the chronological frames of those places. They will have only that 2-3 minutes of the time window to understand what happened there and how to avoid it by tweaking the event in real-time.    Interesting

text: Here is my take - The theme is quite simple. Espionage / Doomsday film. They somehow figure out a way to travel bit ahead in time.. maybe few seconds (10sec-tenet!) and come back in reverse, literally.. against arrow of time; trying to catch / anticipate the exact moment of threat and stop it. Things happen in real time and with arrow of time but from protagonist perspective it happens in reverse.. car accident, bullets on windows, ship in reverse scenes. Nolan will definitely mix it up and show frames from either perspectives and viewers need to figure out who’s perspective they are watching at any given moment. Hence the palindrome name too.. TENET! 😉 It’s a beautiful take on arrow of time linked with second law of thermodynamics. So the visuals and VFX will be mind blowing and confusing and hence the high budget production. Memento skipped to frames in reverse chronology and then showed them forward but tenet will show the frames in reverse literally intermingled with natural flow. Very neat and smart!

I feel like I will witness a tragedy live , a really messed up one too . There will be no way out of it because of how beatifully it is  presented , but the scars will be deep . text: Normally, when the Academy honors "original screenplays" they tend to be small-budget independent films. It isn't simply a case of genre snobbery, but rather that most big budget films that get made are either sequels or based on some established intellectual property (book, TV show, graphic novel) familiar to the audience. Except in the case of Christopher Nolan. Warner Bros. trusts Nolan enough to give him a $100M budget on a truly original film that nobody has any idea what it's about---and Nolan rarely disappoints.

text: I haven't heard a lot about this Christopher Nolan but ever since the Inception of his first movie, I think he'll be able to create fantastic movies that have ideas and themes that transcend Interstellar travel. I am not sure but I think he spends his energy working on projects until it is a Dark Knight. In fact, I heard that his best work is when the sun goes down and the Dark Knight Rises. Due to that, he ended up not being able to sleep and contracted Insomnia. That being said, The Prestige of that man does not allow him to stop from working properly. I've been Following his story for quite some time and I noticed when reading his Memento that he actually loves Batman. Begins the journey of this great man, like the journey of those civilians who trekked their way into Dunkirk. The Tenet of this guy's filmmaking approach is that he does not like CGI but would prefer to have everything done practically. I'm not sure on that, with this approach, he would not be able to make epic scale movies... Now, where was I?

text: I remember I had a Bad Trip after smoking up a bad shit. With a numb body, I was able to see everything and I still remember each and every part of it but couldnt respond to anything. My friends were very scared watching me like this. I was numb for more than an hour and throughout the time I just spoke for like 4-5 words and that was “So this is what happens” in front of my friends. Inside my head, I was completing the sentence “so this is what happens AFTER DEATH.” So I was experiencing that I was dead already and everything is going on the backward side and it will be like this till the day I was born(the day I would come alive again). This is not any made up story. It could be because of ,I so believe in time travelling and I seek for answers that are unknown or may be hallucinations. This movie trailer reminds me of that situation.

This accounts for all physical laws but one, namely, the second law of thermodynamics. However, the theory says  that even the second law of thermodynamics can be reversed. According to Maxwell, this reversal was actually theoretically possible which he explained in his "sorting demon" hypothetical experiment. text: Christopher Nolan (The Dark Knight, Dunkirk, Interstellar, Inception, The Prestige) is one of the most most public advocate's of Movie Theaters. Personally, I think the silver screen is the most true way to experience good film.   Recently, Universal Studios announced they will release streaming releases the same time they premier theatrical premiers. This is going to KILL theaters nation-wide.  Blockbuster is a time of the past, but I think forcing theaters to close their doors will ensure mass societal buyers remose. Regardless of the Netflix convenience factor or the financial savings of having a big family expense; theaters provide a lifelong service.   Christopher Nolan's new movie TENET is tentatively the first big-buget blockbuster movie to premiere after the mass economic shutdown. It's the support of this film that most likey will enforce or devalue the point of Universal Studios.  Absolutely support your local restaurant, but support your local theater too!

text: My best guess about this movie is that there's a secret piece of tech that can somehow tap into and manipulate anti-time. Whatever vehicle or method being used is probably referred to as "Tenet". Theoretically, anti-time flows in the exact opposite direction of real time, so past events in real time invariably become future events in anti-time (and vice versa). Keep in mind, real time is relative to the perspective of the user. Tenet may allow the user to alter critical future events in anti-time using knowledge of the same exact events that already happened in real time's past. Thus, tapping into and manipulating anti time's future is actually altering real time's past. The opposite is theoretically true, so perhaps Tenet also allows the user to alter his future using the same methodology in reverse. This seems like it would be an incredibly coveted & priceless tool to have so I'm sure lots of ridiculously powerful people & entities want or already have access to it. Enter all the big players - Caine, Pattinson, Branagh, some secret government agency, etc. Moving between realms is probably dangerous which may explain why some characters are wearing gas masks. Could be some sort of chemical that sustains a person's sanity while he navigates through an anti-time world. The flow of time is opposite in every sense of the word, so communication, time, perception of reality, etc. is most likely incomprehensible to the mind of someone who experiences real time (and vice versa). Also, I would guess that the time flow physics is reversed for objects that cross realms as well. That's why his bullets were "caught" and that gear "dropped up" into his hand. Notice he's wearing a green glove in both shots. Probably to avoid some sort of quantum annihilation.

text: Imagine if "The Dark Knight Trilogy" is not even your best work. Christopher Nolan is a god among Hollywood film makers.  So much of Hollywood is filled with garbage and desperate movies that are completely awful or middling at best. Everything he does is so spectacular that the Batman series is probably in the middle of his best pieces.  How do you even rate these without saying almost all of them are great?  Even his lower rated movies when he was younger are still fantastic.  In no particular order: -Inception -Interstellar -Memento -Dunkirk -Batman Begins -The Dark Knight -The Dark Knight Rises -Following -The Prestige -Insomnia How can anyone even rate these movies without saying they are all great? Some of you may think whats "Time" got to with the word "TEN-TEN" well a lot actually, All the wrist watches are initially set "Time" as "10:10" paying homage to the inventor of the watch a dutch scientist and mathematician, Christiaan Huygens, who invented the first pendulum clock. the time "10:10" was his eureka moment. so that's why all the dials of wrist watch are set as "10:10" thus the idea in the name of the movie with respects to "Time inversion" also Lincoln was shot at "10:15" five minutes after he sat down..yes, if he decided to walk away before the watch hit "10:10" would be alive..thus "Time Inversion"  Christopher Nolan is genius!!

text: The word TENET is a palindrome. That could be a thematic idea of this new film cleverly captured in the title. The thematic idea being that something can exist that is the same forward as it is backwards. In fact the trailer already shows several instances of time reversal. And after all many of Nolan's films deal with the bizarre philosophies of time and time dilation and expansion (Memento, Inception, Interstellar, Dunkirk). Maybe this film is about mirrored time? I doubt this is true but I wouldn't put it past Nolan to design something in a 5 act way 1. T 2. E 3. N 4. E 5. T. Act 1 and 5 will be mirrors of eachother (Both T), 2 and 4 as well (Both E) and 3 will be the standalone middle act that is itself some dramatic mirror sequence of itself. Even the symbol of the letter N has a certain mirrored dual symmetry to it. So perhaps this whole film will be sort of cyclical , so that it ends where it begins and vice versa, the way the word TENET does, in an bizarre, Nolanesque  mind fuck sort of way. You heard it here first.
